{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Project: Generative Synthetic Wine Sommelier & Critic\n",
    "### Created with AI Collaboration\n",
    "\n",
    "**Design Choice & Architecture:**\n",
    "In this project, we move away from textbook classification loops and instead implement an advanced generative-evaluation framework. We pair a **Generative Density Estimator** (Gaussian Mixture Model) with a **Discriminative Classifier** (Logistic Regression). \n",
    "\n",
    "The GMM learns the underlying continuous joint probability distribution of the chemical features of real wines, allowing us to sample completely new, synthetic observations. The Logistic Regression model acts as a \"Sommelier Critic,\" validating whether our generated profiles align with the mathematical boundary signatures of known real wine categories."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np
",
    "import pandas as pd
",
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_wine
",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
",
    "from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
",
    "from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 1: Load and Prepare Real World Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "wine = load_wine()
",
    "X = wine.data
",
    "y = wine.target
",
    "feature_names = wine.feature_names
",
    "class_names = wine.target_names
",
    "
",
    "# Split data into training and validation sets to establish realistic baseline conditions
",
    "X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42, stratify=y)
",
    "
",
    "# DESIGN CHOICE: Both GMMs and Logistic Regression are highly sensitive to feature scales 
",
    "# (e.g., comparing Alcohol percentage numbers directly to Malic Acid levels). Standardizing ensures stable convergence.
",
    "scaler = StandardScaler()
",
    "X_train_s = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
",
    "X_val_s = scaler.transform(X_val)
",
    "
",
    "print(f"🍷 Loaded Wine dataset with {X_train_s.shape[0]} training samples and {X_train_s.shape[1]} chemical features.")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 2: Train Model 1 - The Sommelier Critic (Logistic Regression)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# This model learns the linear multi-class boundary hyperplanes separating the 3 classes of wine.
",
    "critic = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42)
",
    "critic.fit(X_train_s, y_train)
",
    "
",
    "val_preds = critic.predict(X_val_s)
",
    "baseline_acc = accuracy_score(y_val, val_preds)
",
    "print(f"📊 Baseline Critic Accuracy on Real Validation Data: {baseline_acc:.3%}")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 3: Train Model 2 - The Synthetic Wine Generator (Gaussian Mixture Model)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# DESIGN CHOICE: Instead of just using clustering to group items, we use GMM as a generative density estimator. 
",
    "# We fit 3 mixture components corresponding to our 3 known types of wine.
",
    "generator = GaussianMixture(n_components=3, covariance_type='full', random_state=42)
",
    "generator.fit(X_train_s)
",
    "
",
    "# WHAT I LEARNED: A GMM captures the continuous mean vectors and covariance matrices of high-dimensional spaces, 
",
    "# allowing us to use `.sample()` to generate entirely new, structurally realistic synthetic rows.
",
    "print("🪄 Generative GMM Sommelier trained successfully.")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 4: Generate Synthetic Wines & The Ultimate Evaluation Pipeline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Generate 30 brand-new synthetic wine data points from our trained probability distribution
",
    "n_synthetic_samples = 30
",
    "X_synthetic_s, _ = generator.sample(n_samples=n_synthetic_samples)
",
    "
",
    "# Inverse transform the data just so we can inspect it in its raw, human-readable chemical format
",
    "X_synthetic_raw = scaler.inverse_transform(X_synthetic_s)
",
    "df_synthetic = pd.DataFrame(X_synthetic_raw, columns=feature_names)
",
    "
",
    "# Put our synthetic wines to the test: pass them through the Critic to see if they hold up
",
    "synthetic_predictions = critic.predict(X_synthetic_s)
",
    "critic_confidence = critic.predict_proba(X_synthetic_s).max(axis=1)
",
    "
",
    "df_synthetic['Assigned Class'] = [class_names[p] for p in synthetic_predictions]
",
    "df_synthetic['Critic Confidence'] = critic_confidence"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 5: Results Evaluation and Interpretation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    print("="*60)
",
    print("RESULTS AND PERFORMANCE INTERPRETATION")
",
    print("="*60)
",
    print(f"• Average Critic Confidence on Synthetic Wines: {np.mean(critic_confidence):.2%}")
",
    print("\n• First 5 Synthesized Wine Chemistry Profiles passed through the Critic:")
",
    print(df_synthetic[['alcohol', 'malic_acid', 'ash', 'Assigned Class', 'Critic Confidence']].head())
",
    "
",
    print("\n• Distribution of Generated Wine Classes:")
",
    print(df_synthetic['Assigned Class'].value_counts())
",
    "
",
    "# FINAL CONCLUSION: 
",
    "# If the Critic classifies the synthetic samples with high confidence (e.g., >85%), 
",
    "# it proves our GMM generator successfully captured the true underlying mathematical 
",
    "# structure of the wine dataset, creating valid synthetic variants rather than random noise."
   ]
  }
 ],
